  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Making use of a recently proposed formalism, we analyze the composite nature of the <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>4450</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> resonance observed by LHCb. We show that the present data suggest that this state is almost entirely made of a <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>χ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math> and a proton, due to the close proximity to this threshold. This also suppresses the decay modes into other, lighter channels, in our study represented by <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Ψ</mi><mi>p</mi></math> . We further argue that this is very similar to the case of the scalar meson <math altimg="si5.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>980</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> which is located closely to the <math altimg="si10.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>K</mi><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover></math> threshold and has a suppressed decay into the lighter ππ channel.</subfield>
